From TableÂ I, we can see that the non-private FedAvg achieves a testing accuracy of 86.61%percent86.6186.61\% on Fashion-MNIST dataset. When adding Gaussian noise to ensure (1.01,nâˆ’1.1)1.01superscriptğ‘›1.1(1.01,n^{-1.1})-DP, the accuracy drops to 71.40%percent71.4071.40\% for DP-FedAvg. By choosing a proper value of pğ‘p, Fed-SMP can reach a higher accuracy than DP-FedAvg under the same level of DP guarantee. For the communication cost, we can observe from TableÂ I-III that the uplink communication cost for Fed-SMP on both datasets is relatively lower than that of DP-FedAvg and FedAvg under the same privacy guarantee, since our scheme integrates well with the secure aggregation protocol and takes advantage of model update compression. To further demonstrate the communication efficiency of Fed-SMP, we show the convergence speed and communication cost of our Fed-SMP algorithms. Specifically, we select the Fed-SMP algorithms with the optimal compression ratio and show its testing accuracy with respect to the communication round and uplink communication cost in Fig.Â 2, compared with DP-FedAvg and FedAvg: For Fashion-MNIST dataset, we draw the results of Fed-SMP-topksubscripttopğ‘˜\operatorname{top}_{k} with p=0.005ğ‘0.005p=0.005 and Fed-SMP-randksubscriptrandğ‘˜\operatorname{rand}_{k} with p=0.4ğ‘0.4p=0.4, while achieving (1.01,nâˆ’1.1)1.01superscriptğ‘›1.1(1.01,n^{-1.1})-DP; for SVHN dataset, we draw the results of Fed-SMP-topksubscripttopğ‘˜\operatorname{top}_{k} with p=0.01ğ‘0.01p=0.01 and Fed-SMP-randksubscriptrandğ‘˜\operatorname{rand}_{k} with p=0.4ğ‘0.4p=0.4, while achieving (1.01,nâˆ’1.1)1.01superscriptğ‘›1.1(1.01,n^{-1.1})-DP; for Shakespeare dataset, we draw the results of Fed-SMP-topksubscripttopğ‘˜\operatorname{top}_{k} with p=0.05ğ‘0.05p=0.05 and Fed-SMP-randksubscriptrandğ‘˜\operatorname{rand}_{k} with p=0.2ğ‘0.2p=0.2, while achieving (6.99,nâˆ’1.1)6.99superscriptğ‘›1.1(6.99,n^{-1.1})-DP.

From TableÂ I-TableÂ III, we have observed that as compression ratio pğ‘p decreases from 1.0 to a small value (e.g., 0.005), the testing accuracy of Fed-SMP first increases and then decreases. Note that here we vary the noise multiplier Ïƒğœ\sigma to achieve different privacy losses. Furthermore, we also observe that under the same privacy loss, the testing accuracy of Fed-SMP always increases at first and then decreases, as the compression ratio pğ‘p increases. As Ïµitalic-Ïµ\epsilon decreases, the noise multiplier Ïƒğœ\sigma increases, and thus, the privacy error increases. In this case, the optimal pğ‘p should decrease to reduce the privacy error.
